name: 2-fluoroquinoline-3-boronic acid
Reason: 2-fluoroquinoline-3-boronic acid has a melting point that can be predicted by considering its structural components. The basic unit for comparison is 3-fluorobenzene, which has a melting point of -10.5 °C. The fluorine atom introduces a significant dipole, increasing intermolecular forces and melting point by approximately +10 °C. The quinoline ring introduces additional rigidity and pi-system, estimated at around +20 °C. The boronic acid moiety introduces a hydroxyl group, which can participate in hydrogen bonding, raising the melting point by approximately +5 °C. The presence of two methoxy groups can also contribute to the melting point, estimated at around +2 °C each.
